Ukraine on its way to Europe
"East is East and West is West, and never the twain shall meet," said Rudyard Kipling once.
The Ukraine lies undoubtedly in the East, but in Eastern Europe.
When the country regained its independence ten years ago, European integration became the dominant goal for many of us.
The path there was not always paved with success, if it was paved at all.
But the result of the parliamentary elections on March 31st has shown that Ukrainians are still determined to go down this path.
I am a Social Democrat and have never been a member of the communist party, although as a lawyer during the Soviet Union I was certainly successful.
It is beyond question to me that our "Soviet" legacy is largely responsible for Ukraine's difficulties in aligning with Europe.
After the collapse of the USSR, the country had an inefficient and militarized industry as well as an unprofessional bureaucratic apparatus.
The vast agricultural areas were practically paralyzed by outdated machine parks and the inertia of state-run agriculture in the Soviet mold.
The rural population sank deep into dirt and poverty.
Low wages make life here very difficult, pensions are a joke, and the shadow economy is huge.
But our Soviet legacy does not justify everything.
We have bungled the reform all on our own.
Because often we wanted to import proven concepts from the West - private property, free market economy, strict observance of human rights, the creation of civil society, representative democracy - in a watered-down form and thought that this would somehow help us preserve socialist elements.
Despite these nostalgic tendencies in politics, the Supreme Council (the Parliament of Ukraine) over the years has enacted laws on civil rights and criminal law, as well as land, family, and economic rights, which amounts to something like a revolution.
The acceptance of Western values in a society that for centuries had been cut off from European history was often painful, but has gained momentum, although we do not see ourselves as a typical Western nation.
We see ourselves as open, sentimental, friendly, and family-conscious, but also chaotic and indifferent at times, sometimes irresponsible and lazy.
Nevertheless, we are Europeans.
This is visible on the streets and squares of Kyiv.
Today, drivers let pedestrians cross the street, as in Geneva or Munich (while pedestrians in Moscow still have to dodge reckless drivers for safety).
In Kyiv there is now a vibrant café scene and friendly public squares where people can pause and enjoy life.
The young people learn English, German, and French, they can handle computers and surf the internet at Internet cafes.
But these are merely the rhapsodic digressions of someone who loves Kyiv very much.
The sober eye of the career politician I am sees profound changes.
In the last ten years, a development from total rejection of reforms to a policy of half-hearted reforms out of corrupt motives has given way to a gradual introduction of Western practices.
The administrative reform illustrates this very clearly.
At first, the reform of the state elicited hostile feelings among both bureaucrats and ordinary citizens.
A drastic and unconsidered reduction of public servants began.
It was a "F model" reform: it was assumed that the state had to shrink, and then the government would run smoothly.
No one thought about how countries like France or Switzerland manage to thrive with large state apparatuses.
The problem is not only one of size, but also of organization and efficiency.
The realization that the government does not necessarily improve simply by cutting budgets led us to the second stage in our reform process.
Gradually, the state was reformed in a more sensible manner.
New departments and positions for ministers with clearly defined areas of responsibility were established.
Thus, the work of the government ministries became stabilized.
At first, the authority delegated to these new areas was too broad to effectively enhance their work.
Now they function more or less normally.
Ukrainians may sometimes be annoyed by these impersonal modern mechanisms, but they increasingly accept them as necessary (although unwillingly).
Reasonable politicians also accept them.
Only radicals and populists - of whom we still have too many - can afford to adopt an indifferent attitude toward a more efficient state.
The taming of our radicals and the radical impulse was not easy.
Why?
Ukraine was for too long a province of the Soviet Union and the tsarist empire, the most important, but still a province.
This has shaped our mentality. For radicalism is a byproduct of provincial inferiority complexes.
A overwhelming sense of inferiority and our efforts to deny it have led to some of the most scandalous moments in Ukrainian politics.
The provincial cannot acknowledge his own inferiority and refuses to learn from others.
As we shed our provincial urge to defend ourselves, we open ourselves up to the best that others can offer us.
A century ago, the Ottoman Empire was ridiculed as "the sick man of Europe."
Since 1991, Ukrainians have had to acknowledge that their country had inherited this sad title in the eyes of many Europeans.
Over the course of a decade, we may have contributed to becoming even sicker, but the recently held elections, which deprived the Communists of their dominant position in the Supreme Council and significantly reduced the power of the "powerful parties" under President Kuchma, have pushed our provincial radicals to the margins of politics.
The reform parties and the European parties have won.
As European outsiders or, at least, as a people on the edge of Europe, we want to build a society in which there are no outsiders or marginal individuals.
As the great and already American writer Vladimir Nabokov said in the 1970s: "Among all the achievements of nature, the most amazing one is probably the survival of the weakest."
The long, austere path to Europe has helped a weak new nation become strong and survive.
